{{About|the building in Palermo (Italy)|the monument in Aachen|Palatine Chapel, Aachen}}
[[Image:Chapelle Palatine.jpg|thumb|200px|[[Saracen]] arches and Byzantine mosaics complement each other within the Palatine Chapel]]
The '''Palatine Chapel''' ({{lang-it|Cappella Palatina}}), is the royal [[chapel]] of the [[Italo-Normans|Norman]] kings of [[Sicily]] situated on the first floor at the center of the [[Palazzo dei Normanni|Palazzo Reale]] in [[Palermo]], southern [[Italy]].
Also referred to as a ''Palace church'' or ''Palace chapel'',{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=125}} it was commissioned by [[Roger II of Sicily]] in 1132 to be built upon an older chapel (now the crypt) constructed around 1080. It took eight years to build, receiving a royal charter the same year, with the [[mosaic]]s being only partially finished by 1143.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=125}} The sanctuary, dedicated to [[Saint Peter]], is reminiscent of a domed [[basilica]]. It has three [[apse]]s, as is usual in [[Byzantine architecture]], with six pointed arches (three on each side of the central nave) resting on recycled classical [[column]]s.
==Mosaics== [[File:King - Dome interior - Capela Palatina - Palermo - Italy 2015.JPG|thumb|mosaic in the Palatine Chapel]] The [[mosaic]]s of the Palatine Chapel are of unparalleled elegance as concerns elongated proportions and streaming draperies of figures. They are also noted for subtle modulations of colour and luminance. The oldest are probably those covering the ceiling, the drum, and the dome. The shimmering mosaics of the [[transept]], presumably dating from the 1140s and attributed to Byzantine artists, with an illustrated scene, along the north wall, of St. John in the desert and a landscape of ''Agnus Dei''.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=139}} Below this are five saints, the Greek fathers of the church, St. Gregory of Nissa, St. Gregory the Theologian, St. Basil, St. John Chrysostom and St. Nicholas.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=139}} The three central figures, St. Gregory, St. Basil, St. John Chrysostom, allude to the Orthodox cult known as the Three Hierarchs, which originated fifty years earlier.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=139}} Every composition is set within an ornamental frame, not dissimilar to that used in contemporaneous mosaic [[icon]]s. [[Image:Arabischer Maler der Palastkapelle in Palermo 002.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Roger II of Sicily depicted on the [[muqarnas]] ceiling in an [[Islamic art|Arabic style]].]]
The rest of the mosaics, dated to the 1160s or the 1170s, are executed in a cruder manner and feature [[Latin]] (rather than Greek) inscriptions. Probably a work of local craftsmen, these pieces are more narrative and illustrative than transcendental. A few mosaics have a secular character and represent oriental [[flora]] and [[fauna]]. This may be the only substantial passage of secular Byzantine mosaic extant today.
==Chapel== [[File:Cappella Palatina in Palermo Sicily.JPG|thumb|Cappella Palatina in Palermo Sicily]] [[File:Cappella Palatina - sostre.jpg|thumb|[[Muqarnas]], a common element in [[Arabic architecture]]]] The chapel combines harmoniously a variety of styles: the [[Norman architecture]] and door decor, the [[Arabic architecture|Arabic arches]] and script adorning the roof, the [[Byzantine]] dome and mosaics. For instance, clusters of four [[eight-pointed star]]s, typical for Muslim design, are arranged on the ceiling so as to form a Christian [[cross]].
Other remarkable features of the chapel include the [[muqarnas]] ceiling, which is spectacular. The hundreds of facets were painted, notably with many purely ornamental vegetal and [[zoomorphic]] designs but also with scenes of daily life and many subjects that have not yet been explained. Stylistically influenced by Iraqi [[Abbasid Caliphate|'Abbasid art]], these paintings are innovative in their more spatially aware representation of personages and of animals.
The chapel has been considered a union of a Byzantine church sanctuary and a Western basilica nave.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=19}} The sanctuary, is of an "Eastern" artistic nature, while the nave reflects "Western" influences.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=19}}
==Nave== The nave, constructed under Roger II, did not contain any Christian images.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997b|p=110}} These were added later by Roger II's successors, [[William I of Sicily|William I]] and [[William II of Sicily|William II]].{{sfn|Tronzo|1997b|p=110}} The nave's ceiling consists of Arab, Greek and Latin inscriptions.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=19}}
The frame for the royal throne sets against the west wall of the nave.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=142}} There are six steps leading up to where the throne would be, along with two heraldic lions in two roundels upon the spandrels over the throne frame gabel.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=142}}
==Sanctuary== [[File:Christ Pantocrator - Capela Palatina - Palermo - Italy 2015.JPG|thumb|Mosaic of [[Christ Pantocrator]]]] As an expression of Norman culture, St. Dionysius and St. Martin are represented in the sanctuary.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=107}} Mosaics are of Byzantine culture in their composition and subjects.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=20}} The apex of the dome consists of the [[Christ Pantocrator|Pantokrator]], with rows of angels, prophets, evangelists and saints.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=20}} The Byzantine motif ends abruptly with scenes from Christ's life along the south wall of the southern transept arm, while the north wall consists of warrior saints.{{sfn|Tronzo|1997a|p=20}}
==Analysis== Slobodan Ćurčić considers the ''Palatine Cappella'' a reflection of Middle Byzantine art.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=142}} Illustrating architectural and artistic genius to juxtapose Sicily's "''melting pot''" culture.{{sfn|Ćurčić|1987|p=143-144}}
