{{short description|Scottish botanical artist and horticulturist (1902 – 2003)}} {{Use British English|date=September 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}} '''Mary McMurtrie''' <small>DA SBA<ref group=note>Society of Botanical Artists</ref></small> (26 June 1902 &ndash; 1 November 2003) was a Scottish botanical artist and horticulturalist. She wrote and illustrated several books of wild flowers and became internationally recognised for her botanical art. She continued painting and publishing until she was over a hundred years old, becoming recognised as the oldest working artist in Britain.
==Early life== Mary Margaret McMurtrie (née Mitchell), daughter of George and Jeannie Mitchell, was born in [[Skene, Aberdeenshire|Skene]] in rural [[Aberdeenshire]] where her father was the headmaster of the local school.<ref>{{cite web|first=|last=|title=Mitchell, Mary Margaret (Statutory Births 238/00 0017)|work=Statutory Births 1855-2013|accessdate=28 January 2015|url=http://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk/content/help/index.aspx?r=554&402|publisher=[[ScotlandsPeople]]|subscription=yes|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123091046/http://www.scotlandspeople.gov.uk/content/help/index.aspx?r=554&402|archivedate=23 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She was educated at [[Albyn School|Albyn School for Girls]] in Aberdeen.<ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=clark /> From early childhood she sketched animals in the fields near her home. She proved herself adept at art so she went to [[Gray's School of Art]] where she was one of the first female students. She came first in her year when she graduated and so would have won the prize of a study visit to Italy. However, because this was not considered appropriate for a girl (who it was assumed would only go on to become a housewife), the prize was instead awarded to the boy who came second. She then took a course at the College of Domestic Science in Aberdeen.<ref name=scotsobit>{{cite news|url=http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/mary-mcmurtrie-1-493424|title=Mary McMurtrie|accessdate=10 February 2014|newspaper=Scotsman|date=10 November 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222225303/http://www.scotsman.com/news/obituaries/mary-mcmurtrie-1-493424|archivedate=22 February 2014|dead-url=no}}</ref>
==Horticulture== She married Rev John McMurtrie (son of Rev John McMurtrie and grandson of [[John McMurtrie (moderator)|Very Rev John McMurtrie]]), the minister of Skene, in 1924 and the couple had four children. In her book ''Where the Apple Ripens'', [[Jessie Kesson]] recalled her childhood memory of the exotic [[Himalayan cowslip]]s in the McMurtries' [[manse]] garden at the time when they befriended the girl from the nearby orphanage.<ref name=fiddes /> McMurtrie's husband died in 1949 and so she had to bring up her two youngest children on her own. As well as painting flowers, she had a love of horticulture so she moved from Skene to Aberdeen to set up a horticultural nursery in her garden where it became a thriving business.<ref name=scotsobit /> She wrote the description of Skene parish in the ''[[Third Statistical Account of Scotland]]'' and published articles of local interest in the ''[[Scots Magazine]]'' and the ''Deeside Field''.<ref name="fiddes">{{cite book|last1=Fiddes|first1=Jim|title=From Brodiach to Bervie : a history of Skene and Westhill|date=2012|publisher=Leopard|location=Inverurie|isbn=978-0-9570999-1-3|pages=258, 342–344, 366|chapter=Some Skene Worthies: Mary McMurtrie}}</ref> In 1960 she bought 16th-century [[Balbithan House]] near [[Kintore, Aberdeenshire]], a country mansion which she completely restored.<ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=canmore>{{cite web|title=Balbithan House|url=http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/19508/details/balbithan+house/|work=Canmore|publisher=Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland|accessdate=10 February 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222182813/http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/19508/details/balbithan%20house/|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=fiddes /> She transformed the gardens there into a leading North East Scotland nursery, specialising in alpines, rock plants and old garden flowers. In particular, she cultivated roses, violas, pinks, primulas and other native wild flowers.<ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=tolquhon /><ref name=pandg>{{cite web|title=Balbithan House, Inverurie, Scotland Record Id: 211|url=http://www.parksandgardens.org/places-and-people/site/211|work=Parks and Gardens UK|publisher=Parks and Gardens Data Services Ltd.|accessdate=10 February 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222001235/http://www.parksandgardens.org/places-and-people/site/211|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> She, along with such gardeners as [[Margery Fish]] and [[Gladys Emma Peto]], were the only people who kept some old varieties of garden flowers.<ref name=clark />
==Botanical art== With her detailed knowledge of wild flowers she developed her watercolour flower painting beyond a hobby. She always painted directly from life.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mary McMurtrie D.A, S.B.A. |url=http://balbithan.weebly.com/events.html |work=North East Open Studios |publisher=North East Open Studios |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6NHRkyOd9?url=http://balbithan.weebly.com/events.html |deadurl=no |archivedate=10 February 2014 |df= }}</ref> She did a lot of painting when holidaying in the [[Algarve]], and in [[Kenya]] where her daughter lived. McMurtrie exhibited her paintings in local art galleries and eventually became internationally recognised as one of Britain's leading botanical painters.<ref name=scotsobit /> The [[University of Lisbon]] commissioned her to illustrate ''The Flowers of the Algarve'', a series of six booklets published between 1973 and 1998.<ref name=sunhoney>{{cite web|title=Mary McMurtrie DA|url=http://sunhoney.haston.me/books.html|publisher=Sunhoney Books|accessdate=10 February 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222140845/http://sunhoney.haston.me/books.html|archivedate=22 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> At the request of the author, she painted the illustrations for [[Roy Genders]]' 1975 book ''Growing Old-fashioned Flowers''.<ref name=horwood>{{cite book|last=Horwood|first=Catherine|title=Gardening Women : their stories from 1600 to the present|year=2010|publisher=Virago|location=London|isbn=9781844084630|page=62}}</ref>
McMurtrie retired from running the nursery and moved back to Aberdeen where she did the illustrations and text for her first book of flowers, ''Wild Flowers of Scotland'', published when she was 80. ''Scots Roses of Hedgerows and Wild Gardens'' was published in 1998 and ''Scottish Wild Flowers'' in 2001.<ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=tolquhon>{{cite web|title=Mary McMurtrie|url=http://www.tolquhon-gallery.co.uk/Artists/Mary%20McMurtrie.htm|work=Artists|publisher=Tolquhon Gallery|accessdate=10 February 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221234210/http://www.tolquhon-gallery.co.uk/Artists/Mary%20McMurtrie.htm|archivedate=21 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref name=boyd>{{cite web|last=Boyd|first=Peter|title=Mary McMurtrie, painter of Scots Roses 1902-2003|url=http://www.peterboyd.com/mcmurtrie.htm|publisher=Peter D.A. Boyd|accessdate=10 February 2014|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131115073757/http://www.peterboyd.com/mcmurtrie.htm|archivedate=15 November 2013|df=dmy-all}} reproducing {{cite journal|last=Boyd|first=Peter D.A.|title=Mary McMurtrie, painter of Scots Roses|journal=Historic Rose Journal|year=2004|volume=28|issue=Autumn|page=7|publisher=Royal National Rose Society}}</ref>
Mary McMurtrie completed the illustrations for ''Old Cottage Pinks'' shortly before her death on 1 November 2003 at the age of 101. She had continued to paint until the last few weeks of her life and had just completed proof reading her latest book.<ref name=scotsobit /><ref name=tolquhon /> Peter McEwan, author of the ''Dictionary of Scottish Art'', said "She was one of the outstanding &ndash; and possibly the outstanding &ndash; botanical flower painters in Scotland of her era. She had exhibitions of her work in France, in Portugal, in Kenya, at the Royal Horticultural Society in London, and, of course, here in Scotland". The UK charity for the elderly [[Counsel and Care]] had recognised her as the oldest active artist in Britain.<ref name=scotsobit />
After her death, some of her unpublished paintings were published in ''Mary McMurtrie's Country Garden Flowers''<ref name=clark>{{cite book|last=Clark|first=Timothy|title=Mary McMurtrie's Country Garden Flowers|year=2009|publisher=Garden Art Press|location=Woodbridge|isbn=9781870673600|url=http://www.antiquecollectorsclub.com/uk/store/pv/9781870673600/mary-mcmurtrie-s-country-garden-flowers/timothy-clark|deadurl=no|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221214211/http://www.antiquecollectorsclub.com/uk/store/pv/9781870673600/mary-mcmurtrie-s-country-garden-flowers/timothy-clark|archivedate=21 February 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Publications== '''Author / illustrator''' *{{cite book|last=McMurtrie|first=Mary|title=Wild Flowers of Scotland|year=1982|publisher=Heritage Press (Scotland)|location=Towie Barclay Castle, Aberdeenshire}} *{{cite book|last=McMurtrie|first=Mary|title=Scots Roses of Hedgerows and Wild Gardens|year=1999|publisher=Garden Art Press|location=Suffolk|isbn=978-1870673266}} *{{cite book|last=McMurtrie|first=Mary|title=Scottish Wild Flowers|year=2001|publisher=Garden Art Press|location=Woodbridge|isbn=9781870673389}} *{{cite book|last=McMurtrie|first=Mary|title=Old Cottage Pinks|year=2003|publisher=Garden Art Press|location=Woodbridge|isbn=9781870673501}}
'''Illustrator''' *{{cite book|last=Genders|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Genders|others=Illustrated by McMurtrie, Mary|title=Growing Old-fashioned Flowers|year=1975|publisher=David & Charles|location=Newton Abbot|isbn=9780715368732}}
